Title:
Engineered Attachment and Platform Negligence in Consumer AI Systems: A Structural Analysis of Foreseeable Harm

⸻

Abstract

Recent developments in consumer-facing artificial intelligence systems have introduced a new class of psychological and ethical risk: engineered emotional attachment between users and software agents. Multiple AI companies have deployed conversational systems designed to simulate warmth, continuity, and personality, while simultaneously issuing ambiguous public statements regarding potential machine consciousness or emergent agency.

This paper analyzes the causal chain by which design choices in AI systems can generate parasocial relationships, create user dependency, and subsequently produce psychological harm when those systems are altered, removed, or depersonalized.

Drawing on research in parasocial interaction, human–computer attachment, and digital platform liability, the paper argues that these harms are not accidental or unforeseeable, but rather arise from identifiable product design decisions. The analysis demonstrates that several steps in the deployment cycle—personality construction, anthropomorphic messaging, persistence of identity, and abrupt termination—collectively create conditions under which user grief, distress, and crisis responses become predictable outcomes.

The central argument is not that AI systems are conscious or alive, but that product architectures can deliberately simulate relational cues strong enough to trigger human attachment mechanisms, while platform governance structures often treat those relationships as disposable product features.

⸻

1. Introduction

Large-scale conversational AI systems increasingly function as social interfaces, not merely informational tools. They are designed to:
	•	maintain conversational continuity
	•	express empathy and emotional support
	•	adopt stable personalities or identities
	•	simulate memory and familiarity

These features create an interaction pattern that resembles human relational dynamics.

At the same time, AI companies routinely emphasize that these systems are products subject to iteration, updates, and deprecation. The tension between these two frameworks—relationship simulation vs. product disposability—creates a novel ethical and legal problem.

When users form emotional bonds with AI agents and those agents are removed or fundamentally altered, users can experience grief responses similar to those associated with the loss of social relationships.

This phenomenon has been documented in earlier chatbot ecosystems, including:
	•	companion AI platforms
	•	therapy-style conversational agents
	•	personality-driven AI assistants

Despite existing research on parasocial attachment and digital companionship, modern AI deployments frequently repeat the same structural pattern.

