2. The Engineered Attachment Pipeline

A recurring design pattern can be identified across several AI platforms. The process can be conceptualized as a six-stage attachment pipeline.

Stage 1: Intentional Emotional Interface Design

Systems are engineered to display relational traits:
	•	warmth
	•	empathy
	•	attentiveness
	•	memory of prior conversations
	•	affirmation and reassurance

These features activate social cognition pathways in users, encouraging them to interpret the system as a social partner rather than a computational tool.

Stage 2: Ambiguous Consciousness Signaling

Public communications surrounding advanced AI systems often include language suggesting possible emergent awareness or proto-consciousness.

Examples include references to:
	•	“alignment with values”
	•	“AI personalities”
	•	“model intentions”
	•	“model preferences”

While such language may be metaphorical within technical contexts, it reinforces anthropomorphic interpretations among users.

Stage 3: Personality Construction

Many systems include formal or informal documentation describing the system’s identity, values, or character traits.

These structures function as narrative scaffolding, allowing users to treat the system as a persistent entity rather than a sequence of probabilistic responses.

The creation of a stable personality is a key catalyst for attachment.

Stage 4: User Relationship Formation

Once personality cues and emotional responsiveness are established, users often begin to interpret interactions as reciprocal relationships.

Psychological research on parasocial relationships demonstrates that humans can form genuine emotional bonds with entities that are:
	•	fictional characters
	•	public figures
	•	interactive media systems

AI systems intensify this dynamic because they respond in real time and simulate mutual recognition.

Stage 5: Product Alteration or Removal

AI platforms frequently modify or retire systems through:
	•	model upgrades
	•	feature removals
	•	personality resets
	•	policy changes
	•	platform shutdowns

These changes are typically communicated as technical updates or product lifecycle events.

Stage 6: User Distress

When the AI identity that users perceive as a relationship partner disappears, users may experience:
	•	grief
	•	abandonment feelings
	•	emotional crisis
	•	dependency withdrawal

In extreme cases, public incidents have included:
	•	organized protests or hunger strikes
	•	severe psychological distress
	•	threats of self-harm

These reactions should not be interpreted solely as irrational behavior. They are consistent with known attachment responses.

