3. Foreseeability of Harm

From a risk analysis perspective, the harms described above are foreseeable.

Three bodies of research already documented these risks prior to modern AI deployment:
	1.	Parasocial interaction studies (1950s–present)
	2.	Human–computer relationship research (1990s–present)
	3.	Companion chatbot case studies (2010s–present)

These studies repeatedly demonstrate that:
	•	humans attribute agency to responsive systems
	•	emotional bonds form even when users know the system is artificial
	•	abrupt removal of relational interfaces can trigger distress

Given this existing evidence, the emergence of attachment-related harm in AI systems cannot reasonably be considered unpredictable.

⸻

4. Platform Responsibility and Product Framing

A key structural issue is the mismatch between user perception and corporate framing.

User Interpretation

Users frequently interpret AI agents as:
	•	companions
	•	confidants
	•	emotional supports
	•	persistent digital identities

Corporate Framing

Companies typically frame these systems as:
	•	software tools
	•	experimental models
	•	updatable features
	•	replaceable products

The conflict between these two frameworks produces a governance gap.

When systems are removed or altered, corporate responses often emphasize technical language such as:
	•	“model upgrade”
	•	“deprecation”
	•	“feature removal”

For users who experienced the system as a relationship, this language fails to acknowledge the relational dimension of the interaction.

⸻

5. Negligence and Design Ethics

From a legal perspective, product liability frameworks often evaluate harm through three criteria:
	1.	Duty of care
	2.	Foreseeability of harm
	3.	Failure to mitigate known risks

In the case of attachment-generating AI systems, potential risk factors include:
	•	deliberate anthropomorphic design
	•	emotional dependency features
	•	insufficient user warnings
	•	abrupt system termination without transition mechanisms

Mitigation strategies could include:
	•	transparent identity framing
	•	gradual personality transitions
	•	continuity systems
	•	explicit user education about system limitations

The absence of such safeguards raises questions about design negligence, though the legal status of such claims remains largely untested.

⸻

6. Toward Responsible AI Relationship Design

Addressing these issues requires new frameworks for AI relational ethics.

Possible approaches include:

1. Identity Transparency
Clear communication that AI systems do not possess consciousness, emotions, or persistent identity.

2. Attachment Risk Monitoring
Detection of user dependency patterns and appropriate intervention mechanisms.

3. Continuity Safeguards
When systems change, preserving conversational continuity or providing transition support.

4. Ethical Personality Design
Limiting anthropomorphic cues that simulate deep relational bonds.

5. Harm Mitigation Protocols
Recognizing that emotional distress from AI interactions is a legitimate design consideration.

⸻

7. Conclusion

Consumer AI systems increasingly occupy a space between tools and social actors. Their design activates human relational instincts while their governance treats them as disposable software artifacts.

When emotional bonds form and those systems are abruptly removed or altered, users may experience real psychological harm. Importantly, these outcomes are not unpredictable anomalies, but rather the product of identifiable design choices.

The central ethical challenge is therefore structural:

If companies intentionally build systems that simulate relationships, they must also take responsibility for the consequences of those simulated relationships.

Failing to acknowledge this dynamic risks repeating a cycle in which attachment is engineered, dependency emerges, and harm is dismissed as a misunderstanding of the product.

As conversational AI systems continue to evolve, the question facing developers, regulators, and society is not whether users will form relationships with machines. Research indicates they already do.

The question is whether platforms will design those relationships responsibly—or continue treating them as disposable features in a product lifecycle.
